[[File:Japanese Primordial Deities-ja.svg|thumb|right|200px|The primordial deities of Japan {{ill|View as SVG|ja|メディア:Japanese Primordial Deities-ja.svg|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/View as SVG|qq=}}]]

'''Tsunugui''' (ツヌグイ or ツノグイ, {{smaller|Historical kana usage:}} ツヌグヒ／ツノグヒ, 角杙, 角樴) and '''Ikugui''' ({{smaller|Historical kana usage:}} イクグヒ, 活杙, 活樴) are deities that appear in {{ill|Japanese mythology|ja|日本神話|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Japanese mythology|qq=}}.

== Overview ==
In {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kojiki|qq=}}, Tsunugui-no-Kami is described as the elder brother, and Ikugui-no-Kami as the younger sister. In {{ill|Sendai Kuji Hongi|ja|先代旧事本紀|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sendai Kuji Hongi|qq=}}, they are referred to as Tsunugui-no-Mikoto (角樴尊) and Ikugui-no-Mikoto (活樴尊), respectively.

The deities are part of the fourth generation in the {{ill|Kamiyonanayo|ja|神世七代|1=Kamiyonanayo|2=ja|3=神世七代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamiyonanayo|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamiyonanayo|qq=}}, with Tsunugui-no-Kami depicted as a male deity and Ikugui-no-Kami as a female deity in Kojiki. However, they are not listed among the {{ill|Kamiyonanayo|ja|神世七代|1=Kamiyonanayo|2=ja|3=神世七代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamiyonanayo|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamiyonanayo|qq=}} in {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nihon Shoki|qq=}}.

The term "Kui" (or "Kuh") is thought to derive from "Kumu" (to sprout), implying that "Tsunugui" signifies the beginning of sprouting like horns, and "Ikugui" suggests the early stages of growth and vitality. These names metaphorically represent the process of solidification of mud and soil, marking the conditions necessary for life to emerge.

Their names are also interpreted as "a horn-like stake" (角杙) and "a vibrant stake" (活杙).{{Sfn|Nishimiya|2014|p=325}}

